President Biden and President Yoon Suk Yeol of South Korea met to commemorate the 70th anniversary of the U.S.-ROK Alliance. They pledged to strengthen their mutual defense relationship and affirmed their commitment to the combined defense posture under the U.S.-ROK Mutual Defense Treaty. Both countries are committed to peace and stability in the Indo-Pacific region. South Korea expressed confidence in the U.S. extended deterrence commitments and recognized the importance of its reliance on the U.S. nuclear deterrent. The Alliance announced the establishment of a new Nuclear Consultative Group to strengthen extended deterrence and manage the threat posed by North Korea. The United States reiterated its commitment to the defense of South Korea and stated that any nuclear attack by North Korea would be met with a swift and decisive response. Both countries will enhance coordination and visibility of strategic assets, and strengthen bodies for consultations on extended deterrence. They also emphasized the pursuit of dialogue and diplomacy with North Korea for the complete denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.